    story: `<h3>Nepal's Tea Capital</h3><p>Ilam district, bordering India's Darjeeling hills, is the heartland of Nepali tea cultivation. Established by the Rana rulers in the 19th century, the gardens have grown into a thriving industry supplying premium orthodox and CTC teas to global markets. Walking the estate paths at dawn, when mist rolls through the terraced slopes and pickers move gracefully between the rows, is one of eastern Nepal's most memorable experiences.</p><h3>Kanyam: The Green Crown</h3><p>Kanyam village, perched at roughly 1,800 metres, is the centrepiece of the tea belt. Its viewpoints survey a panoramic sweep from the Kanchenjunga massif in the north to the Indian plains in the south. Visitors can join factory tours to witness withering, rolling, oxidising, and firing — the four steps that transform a fresh leaf into a fragrant cup. The nearby Mai Pokhari, a Ramsar-listed sacred wetland, shelters rare orchids, pitcher plants, and hundreds of bird species.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Sunrise panorama of Kanchenjunga from Antu Danda (2,328 m)</li><li>Tea factory tours and plucking demonstrations at Kanyam</li><li>Mai Pokhari sacred wetland and bird-watching sanctuary</li><li>Limbu and Rai cultural homestays and cuisine</li><li>Mechi Highway scenic drive through endless tea gardens</li></ul>`,
