    name: "Pathibhara Devi Temple",
    category: "TEMPLE",
    summary: "Pathibhara Devi Temple is a high-altitude Hindu shrine dedicated to Goddess Durga, set at 3,794 metres in the remote mountains of Taplejung district. Revered equally by Hindus and Buddhists across Nepal and India's Sikkim, it draws more than 30,000 pilgrims annually who undertake a 3\u20134 hour trek from the nearest roadhead. The dramatic Himalayan setting, with views of Kanchenjunga's snowy flanks, makes this one of Nepal's most spiritually charged destinations.",
    story: `<h3>A Goddess Above the Clouds</h3><p>Perched at 3,794 metres in the Taplejung hills of eastern Nepal, Pathibhara Devi Temple is one of the most revered Shakti shrines in the Himalayan region. The goddess, also called Mukhumlung, is believed to grant the wishes of devoted pilgrims who make the arduous trek to her doorstep. Legend holds that the goddess herself selected this commanding ridge, refusing to be housed in the valley below, so that only the truly devoted would reach her.</p><h3>Pilgrimage and Trek</h3><p>The trail begins at Phungling (Taplejung headquarters) or from the roadhead at Kafle Pati, where stone steps and rhododendron forests guide pilgrims upward for three to four hours. Animal sacrifices traditionally accompany major festivals, and the air is thick with incense and the ringing of temple bells during Dashain and Tihar. The site also serves as an alternative entry point for the Kanchenjunga Conservation Area Trek, making it popular with trekkers passing through.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Spectacular views of Kanchenjunga (8,586 m), the world's third-highest peak</li><li>Sacred Hindu-Buddhist confluence site revered across Nepal, Sikkim, and Darjeeling</li><li>Rhododendron forests ablaze with colour in March–April</li><li>Festive atmosphere during Dashain with thousands of pilgrims</li><li>Possible gateway for Kanchenjunga Circuit trekkers</li></ul>`,
