    summary: "The Kanchenjunga Base Camp Trek is one of Nepal's most remote and rewarding wilderness journeys, leading to the base camps of the world's third-highest mountain (8,586 m) in the far eastern corner of the country. The route passes through pristine rhododendron and bamboo forests, traditional Limbu and Sherpa villages, and spectacular high-altitude ridges before reaching Pang Pema (North BC, 5,143 m) and Oktang (South BC, 4,730 m). It remains far less crowded than other Himalayan treks, offering an authentic off-the-beaten-path experience.",
    story: `<h3>The Forbidden Mountain's Footsteps</h3><p>Kanchenjunga, revered as a deity by the Sikkim and Limbu peoples and only opened to climbers in 1955, guards its base camps jealously. The trekking route from Taplejung winds through subtropical lowlands before ascending into a landscape of ancient forests, glacial moraines, and windswept alpine meadows. Each day brings a dramatic change in scenery — from cardamom farms and rice terraces to ice-polished granite and thundering seracs. The region was designated a Conservation Area in 1997 to protect its extraordinary biodiversity.</p><h3>North and South Routes</h3><p>The circuit combines two distinct arms: the northern route climbs to Pang Pema at 5,143 metres, offering a jaw-dropping close-up of Kanchenjunga's north face and the Kangchenjunga Glacier. The southern route descends through Yalung Valley to Oktang at 4,730 metres, where the towering south face reflects in glacial tarns. Connecting the two arms over the challenging Sele La Pass (4,290 m) and Mirgin La (4,663 m) turns the trek into a true circuit adventure requiring experienced mountaineering fitness.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Pang Pema North Base Camp (5,143 m) — closest viewpoint of Kanchenjunga's north face</li><li>Oktang South Base Camp (4,730 m) with Yalung Glacier views</li><li>Pristine forests in Kanchenjunga Conservation Area</li><li>Traditional Limbu and Tibetan-Buddhist cultural villages</li><li>Very low trekker density — true wilderness solitude</li><li>Rich wildlife including red panda, snow leopard, and Himalayan black bear</li></ul>`,
