    name: "Tansen",
    category: "DURBAR_PALACE",
    summary: "Tansen is a beautifully preserved medieval hilltop town and the administrative headquarters of Palpa district, sitting at 1,372 metres on the southern flank of the Mahabharat Range. Its atmospheric Newari bazaar, traditional dhaka weaving, fine metalwork, and commanding Himalayan views have placed it on UNESCO's Tentative World Heritage List. Once a powerful regional capital and a key trade entrep\u00f4t between India and Tibet, Tansen retains an authenticity increasingly rare in Nepal's tourist circuit.",
    story: `<h3>The Newari Kingdom of the West</h3><p>Long before Prithvi Narayan Shah unified Nepal, Tansen was the capital of the Magar Kingdom of Palpa — one of the most powerful principalities in the hills. Under King Mukunda Sen in the 16th century, Palpa nearly conquered Kathmandu, such was its military might. When the kingdom came under Rana influence in the 18th century, Newar merchants transformed Tansen into a prosperous bazaar on the Tibet–India trade route, constructing the ornate courtyard houses and pagoda temples that still crowd its narrow cobbled lanes today.</p><h3>Dhaka and Dhungedhara</h3><p>Tansen is synonymous with two crafts: dhaka weaving — the vibrant geometric fabric woven on traditional hand looms and worn as topis and shawls across Nepal — and dhaulagiri metalwork, producing distinctive black-metal water vessels and figurines. The old bazaar quarter around Shitalpati and Amar Narayan Temple thrums with the sound of looms and the smell of incense. The nearby Mul Dhoka (main gate) features one of the most intricately carved wooden doorways in western Nepal.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Palpa Durbar Square on UNESCO's Tentative World Heritage List</li><li>Amar Narayan Temple — a striking three-tiered pagoda</li><li>Traditional dhaka weaving workshops open to visitors</li><li>Shreenagar Hill panorama: Dhaulagiri to Annapurna and the Terai plains</li><li>Baggi Dhoka — the grand main gate of the old palace complex</li><li>Vibrant local markets selling dhaka cloth, metalwork, and spices</li></ul>`,
