    name: "Rani Mahal Palpa",
    category: "DURBAR_PALACE",
    summary: "Rani Mahal, often called the 'Taj Mahal of Nepal', is a grand neo-classical palace built in 1893 by General Khadga Shamsher Rana on the banks of the Kali Gandaki River in Palpa district. Constructed in memory of his beloved wife Tej Kumari Devi, the white-walled multi-storied structure rises dramatically above the river gorge, blending Rana-era grandeur with a romantic riverside setting. Though now partly restored, it remains one of Nepal's most evocative architectural monuments.",
    story: `<h3>Love in Stone Above the Kali Gandaki</h3><p>In 1893, exiled General Khadga Shamsher Rana channelled his grief at the loss of his wife into creating a monument that would outlast his own sorrow. Rani Mahal — 'Queen's Palace' — rises from a rocky promontory above the thundering Kali Gandaki River in a style that echoes Mughal grandeur while reflecting Rana-era Nepal's infatuation with European classicism. Its arched galleries, ornamental balustrades, and multi-storied towers stare across the gorge at terraced rice fields climbing the opposite hillside — a sight that has long drawn comparisons to the Taj Mahal in its romantic desolation.</p><h3>Abandonment and Rediscovery</h3><p>Just nine years after construction, in 1902, Khadga Shamsher was forced to flee to India following a political upheaval, leaving Rani Mahal abandoned to nature. For decades, jungle vines crept through its corridors and monsoon floods undermined its foundations. Restoration efforts by the Department of Archaeology have slowly stabilised the structure, and it is now accessible via a riverside trail. The journey itself — a 45-minute walk along the river from the roadhead at Rampur — adds to the sense of romantic discovery.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Iconic view of the palace reflected in the Kali Gandaki at sunrise</li><li>Rana-era neoclassical architecture in a dramatic gorge setting</li><li>Riverside walk from Rampur through forests and farmland</li><li>Combination day-trip with Tansen (35 km away)</li><li>Peaceful picnic spot with minimal crowds</li></ul>`,
