    name: "Riri Lake (Ruru Kshetra)",
    category: "LAKE",
    summary: "Riri Lake, also known as Ruru Kshetra or Ridi, is one of Nepal's four sacred Char Dham pilgrimage sites, situated at the confluence of the Ridi Khola and Kali Gandaki River in Gulmi district near Palpa. The site is renowned for its Rishikesh temple \u2014 built by the first king of Palpa, Mukund Sen \u2014 and the abundance of sacred shaligram (ammonite) fossils found in the river bed, which are considered manifestations of Lord Vishnu. Thousands of pilgrims descend on Ridi during the Maghe Sankranti festival in January to bathe in the holy confluence.",
    story: `<h3>One of Nepal's Four Char Dhams</h3><p>Nestled in a deep, narrow river valley at the tri-junction of Gulmi, Palpa, and Syangja districts, Ruru Kshetra — popularly called Ridi — holds a singular place in Hindu cosmology as one of Nepal's four sacred Char Dhams. Ancient Hindu texts identify this confluence as a site of immense spiritual potency where bathing washes away a lifetime of sin and grants moksha — liberation from the cycle of rebirth. The presiding deity, Rishikesh (an aspect of Vishnu), has been worshipped here since the days of the Palpa kingdom.</p><h3>Shaligrams and Sacred Waters</h3><p>What makes Ridi uniquely compelling is the abundance of shaligrams — ammonite fossils embedded in the dark Kali Gandaki riverbed — which Hindus venerate as natural, uncarved images of Vishnu. Pilgrims wade into the shallows to collect these smooth black stones, which are believed to carry the divine presence without requiring consecration. The Rishikesh temple complex, with its tiered pagoda towers and riverside ghats, was originally constructed by Mukund Sen and has been expanded and restored over centuries to its present form.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Sacred Char Dham pilgrimage site — one of four in Nepal</li><li>Rishikesh temple with multi-tiered pagoda architecture</li><li>Shaligram ammonite fossils in the Kali Gandaki riverbed</li><li>Ridi Mela fair during Maghe Sankranti (January) drawing thousands</li><li>Scenic river gorge setting surrounded by forested hills</li></ul>`,
