    name: "Tilicho Lake",
    category: "LAKE",
    summary: "Tilicho Lake in Manang district sits at 4,919 metres above sea level, making it one of the highest lakes in the world and a breathtaking side-trip from the Annapurna Circuit. Fed entirely by glacial melt with no outlet, its waters display an intense turquoise-to-emerald colour from suspended glacial silt, surrounded by the towering walls of the Annapurna and Tilicho Peak (7,134 m) massifs. The 3\u20134 day detour from Manang to the lake and back is one of the most visually spectacular high-altitude hikes in the Himalayas.",
    story: `<h3>A Lake Born of Ice</h3><p>Tilicho Lake occupies a glacially carved bowl at the foot of Tilicho Peak (7,134 m) in the Annapurna Conservation Area, Manang district. It stretches four kilometres in length and 1.2 kilometres wide, yet has no visible outlet — its waters seep through the porous moraines below. This self-contained glacial basin produces a colour so vivid that first-time visitors often stop in stunned disbelief: the lake shifts from deep turquoise to emerald green as clouds and snow-light play across its surface.</p><h3>The Annapurna Circuit's Greatest Side-Trip</h3><p>Most trekkers encounter Tilicho as a two-day out-and-back from Manang (3,540 m) on the Annapurna Circuit. The route crosses a dangerous landslide belt — the infamous 'bad section' — before climbing to Tilicho Base Camp at 4,200 metres, where lodges now operate. A final four-hour ascent from base camp delivers trekkers to the lake shore at 4,919 metres. From the shoreline, the views of Tilicho Peak, Nilgiri North, and the Great Barrier ridge are among the finest in the entire Annapurna region.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>One of the world's highest lakes at 4,919 m</li><li>Extraordinary turquoise-to-emerald glacial colouring</li><li>Framed by Tilicho Peak (7,134 m) and the Annapurna massif</li><li>Possibility of crossing Meso Kanto La (5,100 m) to Jomsom</li><li>Remote, pristine high-altitude environment with minimal crowds</li></ul>`,
