    name: "Rara Lake National Park",
    category: "NATIONAL_PARK",
    summary: "Rara Lake is Nepal's largest lake by area (10.8 km\u00b2) and sits at 2,975 metres within Rara National Park in the remote Mugu district of Karnali Province. Often called the 'Queen of Lakes', its crystal-clear waters change colour with the light from sapphire to silver, encircled by conifer forests sheltering musk deer and Himalayan black bear. Reaching this jewel of the far west requires a flight to Talcha Airport followed by a short trek, making it one of Nepal's most exclusive natural destinations.",
    story: `<h3>The Queen of Nepal's Lakes</h3><p>Rara Lake — fed by eleven streams and draining via a single outlet — is the crown of Nepal's far-western highlands. The lake stretches 5.1 km long and 2.7 km wide, reaching a maximum depth of 167 metres, and its surface lies at 2,975 metres. The colour of the water changes hourly: morning brings a deep sapphire, afternoon a turquoise shimmer, and at sunset, the surface mirrors the golden and crimson hues of the surrounding forest. Rara National Park, Nepal's smallest national park at 106 km², is nevertheless home to 51 mammal species and over 200 bird species.</p><h3>Getting to the Edge of the World</h3><p>Rara's remoteness is its great protector and its greatest challenge. The park lies in Mugu district, one of the most inaccessible districts in Nepal, and for decades had no road link to the outside world. Even today, most visitors fly from Nepalgunj to Talcha Airport and trek 3–4 hours to the lake shore. This exclusivity keeps visitor numbers low and the ecosystem pristine. The park authorities limit fishing and camping, and the surrounding Mugu communities maintain a centuries-old tradition of respectful coexistence with the lake's ecosystem.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Nepal's largest lake at 10.8 km² — remarkably clear and deep</li><li>Vivid colour changes from sapphire to turquoise throughout the day</li><li>Chuchemara Peak (4,039 m) — viewpoint above the lake with Himalayan panorama</li><li>Rich wildlife: musk deer, Himalayan black bear, red panda, over 200 bird species</li><li>Traditional Mugu villages and Tibetan-influenced culture nearby</li><li>One of Nepal's least-visited and most pristine national parks</li></ul>`,
