    name: "Lo Manthang",
    category: "DURBAR_PALACE",
    summary: "Lo Manthang is the ancient walled capital of the Kingdom of Lo (Upper Mustang) in northern Mustang district, sitting at 3,840 metres near the Nepal-Tibet border. Founded in 1380 AD by King Ame Pal, its 856-metre-long mud-brick walls enclose a medieval city of whitewashed houses, four-storey palace ruins, and extraordinary Buddhist temples painted with rare 15th-century murals. Opened to trekkers only in 1992, Lo Manthang remains one of the last living examples of a medieval Tibetan city-state, preserving a culture and landscape seemingly untouched by the modern world.",
    story: `<h3>The Last Forbidden Kingdom</h3><p>For decades after Nepal opened its borders to the world, Lo Manthang remained sealed — a restricted zone where the ancient Kingdom of Lo had survived in near-isolation since the 14th century. When the doors finally opened in 1992, trekkers who made the challenging five-day journey from Jomsom found a walled city that looked as though time had stopped six centuries ago. The mud-brick walls, erected by King Ame Pal in 1380, still encircle the settlement almost intact, and the kingdom's last king, Jigme Dorje Palbar Bista, continued to hold court until the monarchy was formally dissolved in 2008.</p><h3>Temples, Murals, and Desert Canyons</h3><p>Lo Manthang's four main Buddhist temples — Champa Gompa, Thupchen Gompa, Chodhe Gompa, and Mustang Gompa — contain some of the finest 15th-century Tibetan Buddhist murals in existence, comparable to the great monasteries of Lhasa and Ladakh. Restoration projects supported by the American Himalayan Foundation have painstakingly revived these frescoes, and many are now accessible to visitors. The surrounding landscape of the Mustang plateau — a high-altitude desert of ochre, red, and grey eroded canyons, natural caves, and wind-sculpted badlands — frames the walled city in a setting of surreal beauty.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Ancient walled city founded 1380 AD — one of the world's last medieval Tibetan city-states</li><li>Four major 15th-century Buddhist temples with restored Tibetan murals</li><li>Former royal palace of the Kingdom of Lo's last ruling family</li><li>Spectacular Mustang plateau desert canyon landscape</li><li>Tiji Festival (May) — Lo Manthang's most spectacular three-day Buddhist celebration</li><li>Hundreds of cliff-face cave monasteries and Sky Caves in the surrounding valleys</li></ul>`,
